### April 2019
Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, the Health Sciences Library staff began working remotely beginning on March 16, 2020 per University and State leadership. The plot below shows the service trend of tickets for the informationist team in April 2019, as this will be used as a  measure of comparison to see how COVID-19 affected the services we provide. 

```{r, echo=FALSE, warning=FALSE, message=FALSE}
#prepare april 19 dataset 
apr19Tot <- apr2019_pi %>%
  group_by(ymd) %>% 
  count()

#add days
date <- ymd(apr19Tot$ymd)
apr19Tot$day <- wday(date)
apr19Tot$day <- as.character(apr19Tot$day)

#convert days (number) to letter
apr19Tot$day[which(apr19Tot$day == "1")] <- "sunday"
apr19Tot$day[which(apr19Tot$day == "2")] <- "monday"
apr19Tot$day[which(apr19Tot$day == "3")] <- "tuesday"
apr19Tot$day[which(apr19Tot$day == "4")] <- "wednesday"
apr19Tot$day[which(apr19Tot$day == "5")] <- "thursday"
apr19Tot$day[which(apr19Tot$day == "6")] <- "friday"
apr19Tot$day[which(apr19Tot$day == "7")] <- "saturday"

#combined dataset
apr19Tot$year <- "2019"
aprTot$year <- "2020"

apr19Tot$ymd <- as.Date(apr19Tot$ymd)
aprCmb <- rbind(apr19Tot, aprTot)
aprCmb$ymd <- as.Date(aprCmb$ymd)

#separate the column by year, month, date
aprCmb$ymd2 <- aprCmb$ymd
aprCmb <- aprCmb %>% separate(ymd2, c("year", "month", "date"), sep = "-")
aprCmb$date <- as.factor(aprCmb$date)
aprCmb$year <- as.factor(aprCmb$year)
aprCmb$year <- factor(aprCmb$year, level = c("2020", "2019"))

```


```{r, echo=FALSE, warning=FALSE, message=FALSE}
#April 2019 plot 
ggplot(apr19Tot, aes(ymd, n)) + 
  geom_line(color = "#00B2FF") + 
  scale_x_date(date_breaks = "1 day", date_labels = "%b %d", 
               limits = c(as.Date("2019-04-01"), as.Date("2019-04-30"))) +
  ylim(min(apr19Tot$n), 6) +
  labs(title = "zendesk ticket trends for the informationist team (total, april 2019)", 
       subtitle = "N = 48",
       y = "ticket count" , x = "date") +
  theme_classic() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1),
        axis.line = element_line(color = "grey37"),
        axis.ticks = element_line(color = "grey37"), 
        axis.text = element_text(color = "grey37"), 
        axis.title.x = element_text(color = "grey7"), 
        axis.title.y = element_text(color = "grey7"), 
        plot.title = element_text(face = "bold"), 
        plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 10),
        legend.title = element_blank(),
        legend.position = "bottom") 

```


### April 2019 vs. April 2020

Despite the concerns we had that the pandemic may pose an additional challenge in our users  reaching out to us, the data show  an approximate 44% increase in the tickets solved in April 2020 compared to April 2019. Also, the shape of graphs are more or less similar, but magnified in April 2020. This result suggests that the pandemic has had a potentially positive effect on the amount of users seeking our services.  We understand many of our clientele have turned their focus onto seeking guidance for various scholarly projects including those that are COVID-19 related, while other research endeavors have been temporarily put on hold during the pandemic. 

```{r, echo=FALSE, warning=FALSE}
#comparison plot of April 2020 vs April 2019
p1 <-
  ggplot(aprCmb, aes(x = date, y = n, group = year, color = year, linetype = year)) + 
  geom_line() +
  labs(title = "zendesk ticket trends comparison - info team (April 2020 vs 2019)", 
       subtitle = "N(2020) = 69, N(2019) = 48",
       y = "ticket count" , x = "date") +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("#000080", "#00B2FF")) +
  theme_classic() +
  theme(axis.line = element_line(color = "grey37"),
        axis.ticks = element_line(color = "grey37"), 
        axis.text = element_text(color = "grey37"), 
        axis.title.x = element_text(color = "grey7"), 
        axis.title.y = element_text(color = "grey7"), 
        plot.title = element_text(face = "bold"), 
        plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 10), 
        legend.title = element_blank(),
        legend.position = "bottom",
        strip.background = element_blank())

p1

```

### Ticket trends comparison 

The general trend of our top client being VP&S, Mailman, SON, and NYP persists this month. In March 2020, service requests from NYP client declined (2 tickets solved), likely due to a focus on COVID-19 clinical patient care. However, NYP requests for assistance increased once again in April 2020. 

For those who classified themselves as “other," three tickets were from undergrad students and one was from non-CU faculty. 

```{r, echo=FALSE, warning=FALSE, message=FALSE}

aprTot_school <- infoApr20_CLN %>%
